The Grand Historian read the Spring and Autumn Annals, the chronological tables, and the secret records, but whenever he reached King Li of Zhou, he could not help but set down his book and sigh. He said: 'Alas, Master Zhi foresaw it!' When Zhou made ivory chopsticks, Jizi sighed. When the Zhou way declined, poets based themselves on the bedchamber, and 'Guan Ju' was composed. When benevolence and righteousness decayed, 'Lu Ming' criticized it. When it came to King Li, because he hated to hear of his faults, the ministers feared execution and disaster arose. King Li fled to Zhi, and disorder began in the capital. The Gonghe administered government. After this, some ruled by force, the strong oppressed the weak, they raised armies without asking the Son of Heaven. Yet upholding the righteousness of the royal house, they made punitive expeditions as lords of alliances. Politics came from the Five Hegemons, feudal lords acted wantonly, extravagant and lawless, traitorous ministers and usurping sons arose increasingly. Qi, Jin, Qin, and Chu were insignificant in the time of prosperous Zhou, their fiefs only a hundred li or fifty li. Jin blocked the three rivers, Qi faced the eastern sea, Chu bordered the Jiang and Huai, Qin relied on the defenses of Yong province. The four seas rose in succession, replacing each other as hegemonic lords. Those praised and greatly enfeoffed by Wen and Wu all inspired awe and submission. This is why Confucius clarified the way of kings, petitioned more than seventy rulers, but none could employ him. Therefore he observed the western Zhou court, discussed historical records and old traditions, arose in Lu and arranged the Spring and Autumn Annals, recording from Yin above to the capture of the unicorn in Ai below, condensing their wording and style, removing their tedious repetitions, to establish righteous principles. The way of kings was complete, human affairs thorough. The disciples of the seventy worthies orally received his transmitted teachings, for there were passages of criticism, mockery, praise, concealment, and depreciation in the wording that could not be shown in writing. The Lu gentleman Zuoqiu Ming feared that disciples would each follow different doctrines, each comfortable with their own opinions, losing the truth, so based on Confucius's historical records he comprehensively discussed their sayings, completing the Zuo Tradition Spring and Autumn Annals. Duo Jiao wrote a commentary for King Wei of Chu, but the king could not read the entire Spring and Autumn Annals, so he selected successes and failures, finally making forty chapters, calling it the Duo Family Annals. In the time of King Xiaocheng of Zhao, his chancellor Yu Qing selected from the Spring and Autumn Annals above and observed recent trends below, also writing eight chapters, calling it the Yu Family Spring and Autumn Annals. LÃ¼ Buwei was chancellor to King Zhuangxiang of Qin, and also looked up to revere antiquity, edited and collected from the Spring and Autumn Annals, gathered events from the time of the six states, making them into eight surveys, six discussions, and twelve records, calling it the LÃ¼ Family Spring and Autumn Annals. And like Xun Qing, Mencius, Gongsun Gu, and Han Fei and their followers, each collected fragments from the Spring and Autumn Annals' text to write books, differing greatly in their accounts. The Han chancellor Zhang Cang calendared the five virtues, the senior grand master Dong Zhongshu expounded the Spring and Autumn Annals' principles, and wrote quite extensively about them.

The Grand Historian says: The Confucians sever their meanings, the galloping explainers gallop with their words, they do not strive to comprehensively grasp beginning and end; The calendar makers take their years and months, several schools exalt divine destiny, the chronological records and secret accounts only record posthumous titles, their words are concise, but to view the essentials comprehensively is difficult. Therefore I have calendared the twelve feudal lords, from the Gonghe administration until Confucius, making manifest in tables the great outlines of rise and decline criticized by Spring and Autumn Annals and Discourses of the States scholars, written in this chapter as a key summary for those who study and treat ancient texts.
